    <p>The most important number is the <strong>all-in cost</strong> &mdash; the total of every fee layer expressed as a percentage of plan assets. For a well-designed small business plan using index funds, all-in costs should be below 1.0 percent annually, and many modern providers achieve 0.50 percent or less. Use our <a href="/calculators/finance/retirement-savings-calculator/">retirement savings calculator</a> to see how fees impact long-term retirement balances.</p>

    <h3>How Fees Compound Over Time</h3>
    <p>Consider an employee who contributes $500 per month for 30 years and earns 7 percent annual returns before fees. With a plan charging 0.40 percent in total fees, they accumulate approximately $556,000. With a plan charging 1.50 percent in total fees, they accumulate approximately $446,000. That 1.10 percentage point difference in annual fees costs the employee over $110,000 in retirement savings. As a fiduciary, your obligation is to keep plan costs reasonable. Regular fee benchmarking &mdash; comparing your plan's fees to industry averages &mdash; is a best practice every plan sponsor should follow annually.</p>

    <h2>Traditional 401(k) vs Safe Harbor vs SIMPLE IRA</h2>
    <p>Small business owners have three main retirement plan options. Each has different contribution limits, employer requirements, and administrative complexity. The right choice depends on your business size, budget, and goals.</p>

