    <p>The SECURE 2.0 Act introduced a new <strong>super catch-up</strong> provision for participants aged 60 through 63, allowing them to contribute up to $11,250 in additional catch-up contributions instead of the standard $7,500. This is a significant planning opportunity for employees approaching retirement. Use our <a href="/calculators/finance/401k-calculator/">401(k) calculator</a> to see how maximizing contributions affects your retirement projections.</p>

    <h2>Tax Benefits for Employers</h2>
    <p>Offering a 401(k) is not just a recruitment tool &mdash; it provides substantial tax benefits for the business itself.</p>

    <h3>SECURE 2.0 Act Tax Credits</h3>
    <p>The SECURE 2.0 Act, passed in late 2022, dramatically expanded tax credits for small businesses starting new retirement plans. These credits apply for the first three years of a new plan.</p>
    <ul>
      <li><strong>Startup Cost Credit:</strong> Small businesses with up to 50 employees can claim a credit of 100 percent of plan startup costs, up to $5,000 per year for three years. This covers administrative fees, advisory fees, and employee education. Businesses with 51 to 100 employees can claim 50 percent of startup costs up to the same cap.</li>
      <li><strong>Employer Contribution Credit:</strong> A new credit allows small businesses (up to 50 employees) to claim a credit for employer contributions made to the plan. The credit is a percentage of employer contributions (up to $1,000 per employee), starting at 100 percent in years one and two, 75 percent in year three, 50 percent in year four, and 25 percent in year five. This means the government essentially reimburses a significant portion of your employer match for the first few years.</li>
      <li><strong>Auto-Enrollment Credit:</strong> An additional $500 per year tax credit for three years if the plan includes an auto-enrollment feature.</li>
    </ul>

    <h3>Tax Deductions for Employer Contributions</h3>
    <p>All employer contributions to a 401(k) plan &mdash; matching contributions, profit-sharing contributions, and non-elective contributions &mdash; are fully tax-deductible as a business expense. Total deductible contributions cannot exceed 25 percent of the aggregate compensation of all plan participants. For most small businesses, this limit is well above the actual contribution amount. Employer contributions are also exempt from FICA taxes (Social Security and Medicare), saving an additional 7.65 percent compared to paying the same amount as wages.</p>

    <h3>Combining Credits and Deductions</h3>
    <p>The tax credits and deductions can be combined, making the first few years of a 401(k) plan remarkably cost-effective. For example, a business with 10 employees that contributes a 3 percent Safe Harbor match might pay $15,000 in employer contributions. That $15,000 is fully tax-deductible, reducing taxable income. On top of that, the employer contribution credit reimburses a portion of the match directly as a dollar-for-dollar tax credit. Additionally, up to $5,000 in plan administrative costs are covered by the startup cost credit. The net cost of offering the plan in the first three years is often close to zero after accounting for all tax benefits.</p>

    <p>For a complete picture of your retirement planning, explore our <a href="/calculators/finance/break-even-calculator/">break-even calculator</a> to determine how quickly the tax benefits offset the cost of offering a plan.</p>

    <h2>Frequently Asked Questions</h2>

    <h3>What is the cheapest 401(k) provider for a small business?</h3>
    <p>For most small businesses with fewer than 50 employees, Guideline is the most affordable full-service 401(k) provider. Their base plan starts at $49 per month plus $8 per participating employee, with no additional investment fees beyond the underlying fund expense ratios. Employee Fiduciary is another low-cost option at $500 per year flat plus $30 per participant annually, which can be cheaper for businesses with very few employees. Both providers have no hidden fees and include fiduciary support, making them strong choices for cost-conscious small business owners.</p>

    <h3>How long does it take to set up a 401(k) plan for my business?</h3>
    <p>Most modern 401(k) providers can get a plan fully set up in two to four weeks. Online-first providers like Guideline, Human Interest, and Betterment for Business can complete setup in as little as one to two weeks if your payroll system integrates directly. Traditional providers like Fidelity, Vanguard, and Charles Schwab may take three to six weeks due to more paperwork and manual processes. The timeline depends on how quickly you complete plan design decisions such as eligibility requirements, vesting schedules, and employer match formulas, as well as payroll integration setup.</p>

    <h3>Do I have to offer an employer match with a 401(k) plan?</h3>
    <p>No, employer matching contributions are not required for a Traditional 401(k) plan. You can offer a 401(k) with employee-only contributions and no employer match. However, you must still pass annual nondiscrimination testing (ADP and ACP tests) to ensure the plan does not disproportionately benefit highly compensated employees. If you want to avoid nondiscrimination testing entirely, you can set up a Safe Harbor 401(k), which does require an employer contribution &mdash; either a match or a non-elective contribution &mdash; but guarantees the plan passes testing automatically.</p>

